{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13696"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13696"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.59,0.23,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53622"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6312"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39082"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1998"},{"type":"tags","id":"2372"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42909"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53622"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents for a routine follow-up. He has a diagnosis of cerebral palsy. His parents report that he can walk independently in most settings but has difficulty with long distances and balancing on uneven surfaces. He can climb stairs with a railing and has some limitations in running and jumping. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals mild spasticity in the lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following Gross Motor Function Classification System (GMFCS) levels best describes this child\u0027s motor function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Level I","Level II","Level III","Level IV","Level V"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Gross Motor Function Classification System (GMFCS) is a standardised tool used to categorise the motor abilities of children with cerebral palsy. Based on the description provided, this child\u0027s functional abilities align most closely with \u003Cstrong\u003ELevel II\u003C/strong\u003E on the GMFCS scale.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChildren classified as \u003Cstrong\u003ELevel I\u003C/strong\u003E on the GMFCS typically have minimal limitations in their mobility. They can walk, run, and jump with relative ease, although speed, balance, and coordination may be slightly impaired. The boy in this scenario has more significant limitations than would be expected for Level I.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevel III\u003C/strong\u003E on the GMFCS describes children who require assistive devices, such as crutches or walkers, for indoor mobility. They may use wheelchairs for longer distances. This level of impairment is more severe than what is described for this patient, who can walk independently in most settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChildren at \u003Cstrong\u003ELevel IV\u003C/strong\u003E have significantly limited self-mobility. They may use powered mobility devices and typically require assistance for transfers. This level of impairment is much more severe than what is described in the scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevel V\u003C/strong\u003E represents the most severe level of motor impairment on the GMFCS. Children at this level have very limited voluntary control of movement and require extensive assistance for all activities. This is clearly not applicable to the child described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the child\u0027s ability to walk independently in most settings, climb stairs with a railing, and perform some running and jumping, albeit with limitations, is most consistent with GMFCS Level II. This classification helps guide expectations for future development, inform treatment planning, and facilitate communication among healthcare providers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Gross Motor Function Classification System (GMFCS) is used to classify the severity of motor function impairment in children with cerebral palsy.","GMFCS Level II indicates that the child can walk in most settings but may have difficulty with long distances and balancing on uneven surfaces."],"references":["GMFCS. In: Cerebral Palsy Alliance [online]. 2023. Available at: https://cerebralpalsy.org.au/cerebral-palsy/gross-motor-function-classification-system/","Piscitelli D, Ferrarello F, Ugolini A, Verola S, Pellicciari L. Measurement properties of the Gross Motor Function Classification System, Gross Motor Function Classification System-Expanded \u0026 Revised, Manual Ability Classification System, and Communication Function Classification System in cerebral palsy: a systematic review with meta-analysis. Dev Med Child Neurol. 2021 Nov;63(11):1251-1261.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34028793/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39082"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13696"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39082"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T13:23:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T13:25:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6312"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53622"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":nul